text.en_US: Check out that view!
Too bad it isn't a reachable area.
See that mountain? You can't climb it.
You ever wonder why it isn't snowing outside the window?
'Cause if I walk right out the front door, it is snowing outsite.
I think that's because the snow is virtual.
Oh, really? Then they should render virtual snow outside the window too!
It seems like a graphical oversight. Perhaps we should make a mod to fix that.
So this is that super overpowered guard art you guys have?
Yeah, dude! It's a total cheeseball of a move.
Gives you three whole seconds of glorious invincibility!
Wow, really? And I thought I was supposed to be the tank class!
Are you sure you didn't mod the stats at all?
No way, dude! The only modded part is you equipping it as a custom skill.
I wonder what other powerful arts all the other classes have.
Custom skills allow you to override the combat arts in your skill tree from a wide variety of other art options. These could be arts from other classes, other mods, or even unique bonus arts.

Custom skills are a normally-dormant feature of the \c[3]Arcane Lab\c[0] mod. \c[3]XPC\c[0] adds many custom skills for specific characters using this system. This allows for a wider variety of combat arts to be available than what can normally be found in a character's skill tree.
The custom skill menu will be locked for any art slots you don't already have unlocked in the circuit skill tree. These will unlock naturally as you unlock regular combat arts in your skill tree.
The \c[3]Custom C. Preset\c[0] item is found in your inventory at the bottom of the \c[3]Add-Ons\c[0] category. This item toggles custom skills as a whole on and off.

Even with custom skills equipped in the custom skill menu, they won't take effect unless \c[3]Custom C. Preset\c[0] is turned on. Likewise, turning on \c[3]Custom C. Preset\c[0] won't have any effect if you don't actually equip any skills in the custom skill menu.
This item can be toggled at any time from the inventory menu.

Current supported characters:
\i[class-sphero]\c[3]Lea\c[0] - 142 custom skills
\i[class-tri]\c[3]Triblader2/3/4/5\c[0] - 5 custom skills
\i[class-tri]\c[3]Schneider/Luke\c[0] - 5 custom skills
\i[class-tri]\c[3]Triblader Lea\c[0] - 5 custom skills
\i[class-hexa]\c[3]Hexacast1/2\c[0] - 245 custom skills

Custom skills will only appear in the menu for supported characters. If you ever change your player character \c[1]after\c[0] equipping custom skills, you must disable them again or else the game will crash when you try to attack.

Even though swapping to an unsupported character will cause the skills to disappear from the custom skill menu, you will still have them equipped after swapping. The custom skill logic is blind to the player swapping characters.

With that in mind, trying to use custom skills with a character they are not designed for will result in a crash. Disabling \c[3]Custom C. Preset\c[0] or unequipping all custom skills will prevent them from being used, and prevent crashes if you ever swap to an unsupported character after equipping custom skills.
That \c[3]overclock\c[0] ability is so cool!
Yeah, it's the only thing that makes Triblader bearable to play.
It feels crazy to go so fast! I can barely keep up with my own movements!
You want to go even faster? Try combining Triblader's \c[3]overclock\c[0] with Hexacast's \c[3]temporal miasma\c[0].
Both of these stack with each other, making you able to move at light speed.
Wow, really? I am going to go try that out right away!

But I've progressed too far to restart...
You can punch your way through anything!
Wouldn't you rather have a cool sword, or smack things with a giant shield?
I guess I could always pick the arts I want using custom skills.
